oducing good readers by the hundreds, many more thousands of bad readers were learning elsewhere to be disciplined public communicators, whether in diplomatic and ambassadorial missions, private and public cultural exchange programs, multinational corporations, or global activist groups. As we grapple with literature's diminished role in the public sphere, Paraliterary suggests a new way to think about literature, its audience, and its potential, one that looks at the civic institutions that have long engaged readers ignored by the academy.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aBooks and readingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBooks and readingzUnited StatesxSociological aspects. 0aBooks and reading--United States--History--20th century. 0aCommunication in international relationszUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited States. 0aReadingxPhilosophy. 4acultural diplomacy. 4ainstitutional sociology. 4aparaliterary. 4apostwar literature. 4asociology of reading. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226474021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226474021.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles